<td>tibi</td>
<td>vōbīs</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Accusative</b></th>
<td>mē</td>
<td>nōs</td>
<td>tē</td>
<td>vōs</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Vocative</b></th>
<td>——</td>
<td>——</td>
<td>tū</td>
<td>vōs</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Ablative</b></th>
<td>mē</td>
<td>nōbīs</td>
<td>tē</td>
<td>vōbīs</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><small><sup>1</sup>—may be <i><b>nostrī</b></i> or <i><b>vestrī</b></i></small></p>
<p>Usually, to show the ablative of accompaniment, <i>cum</i> would be added to the ablative form. However, with personal pronouns and the interrogative (not with 3rd person), <i>cum</i> is added on to the end of the ablative form. For example: <i>mēcum</i>, <i>nōbīscum</i>, <i>tēcum</i>, <i>vōbīscum</i> and <i>quōcum</i> (sometimes <i>quīcum</i>).</p>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr>
<th rowspan="2"></th>
