<p><a name="Adjectives" id="Adjectives"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_declension&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Adjectives">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Adjectives</span></h2>
<p><a name="First_and_second_declension_adjectives" id="First_and_second_declension_adjectives"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_declension&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: First and second declension adjectives">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">First and second declension adjectives</span></h3>
<p>First and second declension are inflected in the masculine, the feminine and the neuter; the masculine form typically ends in <i>–us</i> (although some end in <i>-er</i>, see below), the feminine form ends in <i>–a</i>, and the neuter form ends in <i>–um</i>. Therefore, adjectives are given like <i>altus</i>, <i>alta</i>, <i>altum</i>.</p>
