<p><a name="First_and_second_declension_.E2.80.93r_adjectives" id="First_and_second_declension_.E2.80.93r_adjectives"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_declension&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: First and second declension –r adjectives">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">First and second declension <i>–r</i> adjectives</span></h4>
<p>Some first and second declension adjectives' masculine form end in an <i>–er</i>. As with second declension nouns –r nouns, some adjectives retain the <i>e</i> throughout inflection, and some omit it. <i>Sacer</i>, <i>sacra</i>, <i>sacrum</i> omits its <i>e</i> while <i>miser</i>, <i>misera</i>, <i>miserum</i> keeps it.</p>
