<small>²—may end in <i><b>–e</b></i></small></p>
<p><a name="Third_declension_adjectives_with_two_endings" id="Third_declension_adjectives_with_two_endings"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_declension&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Third declension adjectives with two endings">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Third declension adjectives with two endings</span></h4>
<p>Third declension adjectives that have two endings have one form for the masculine and feminine, and a separate form for the neuter. The ending for the masculine and feminine is <i>–is</i>, and the ending for the neuter is <i>–e</i>. Because the sexed form ends in an <i>–is</i>, we find the adjective genitive singular.</p>
