<p><a name="Third_declension_adjectives_with_three_endings" id="Third_declension_adjectives_with_three_endings"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_declension&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Third declension adjectives with three endings">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Third declension adjectives with three endings</span></h4>
<p>Third declension adjectives with three endings have three separate nominative forms for all three genders. Like third and second declension –r nouns, the masculine ends in an <i>–er</i>. The feminine ends in an <i>–ris</i>, and the neuter ends in an <i>–re</i>. With that information, we come upon the genitive singular needed for inflection, the feminine form.</p>
