<tr>
<th><b>Genitive</b></th>
<td>trium</td>
<td>trium</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Dative</b></th>
<td>tribus</td>
<td>tribus</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Accusative</b></th>
<td>trēs, trīs</td>
<td>tria</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Vocative</b></th>
<td>trēs</td>
<td>tria</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Ablative</b></th>
<td>tribus</td>
<td>tribus</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The word <i>mīlle</i>, is singular, an adjective and indeclinable. However, its irregular plural, <i>mīlia</i>, is a plural noun and is used in the same way <i>plūs</i> is.</p>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr>
<th rowspan="2"></th>
<th colspan="2"><b><i>mīlia, mīlium</i><br />
(a) thousand n.</b></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th colspan="3"><b>Plural</b></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Nominative</b></th>
<td>mīlia</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Genitive</b></th>
<td>mīlium</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Dative</b></th>
<td>mīlibus</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Accusative</b></th>
<td>mīlia</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Vocative</b></th>
<td>mīlia</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><b>Ablative</b></th>
<td>mīlibus</td>
</tr>
</table>
<ul>
<li>Note that to write the phrase "four thousand horses" in Latin, the genitive is used: "quattuor milia equōrum", literally, "four thousands of horses".</li>
</ul>
<p>As stated before, the rest of the numbers are indeclinable adjectives. They are also indeclinable as substantives.</p>
